<subSubSection lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1436,1820,2026]" lastBlockId="38.[151,1436,152,564]" lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,547,1961,1987]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Distribution and ecology:—</emphasis>
Fairly common in humid forests at 
<quantity box="[968,1102,1962,1988]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" unit="m" value="550.0" valueMax="800.0" valueMin="300.0">300–800 m</quantity>
in southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1296,1371,1962,1988]" name="Brazil" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, with isolated, outlying populations in Amazonian (Amazonas) and southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[1061,1134,2000,2026]" name="Brazil" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1150,1394,2000,2026]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso do Sul" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Mato Grosso do Sul</collectingRegion>
) as well as at 
<quantity box="[273,437,152,178]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.625" metricValueMax="2.75" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="2625.0" valueMax="2750.0" valueMin="2500.0">2500–2750 m</quantity>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[477,564,152,178]" name="Bolivia" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(La Paz). This peculiar geographical distribution pattern is also found in other unrelated taxa, e.g., the cactus 
<taxonomicName authority="Haworth (1830: 112)" authorityName="Haworth" authorityPageNumber="112" authorityYear="1830" box="[590,1095,190,216]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Rhipsalis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cereuscula">
<emphasis box="[590,836,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Rhipsalis cereuscula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Haworth, A. H." box="[845,1095,190,216]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="106 - 118" refId="ref31461" refString="Haworth, A. H. (1830) Decas duodecima Novarum Plantarum Succulentarum. The Philosophical Magazine, or Annals of chemistry, mathematics, astronomy, natural history, and general science 7: 106 - 118." type="journal article" year="1830">Haworth (1830: 112)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ibisch, P. L. &amp; Kessler, M. &amp; Nowicki, C. &amp; Barthlott, W." box="[1112,1328,190,216]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="2 - 30" refId="ref31762" refString="Ibisch, P. L., Kessler, M., Nowicki, C. &amp; Barthlott, W. (2000) Ecology, biogeography and diversity of the Bolivian epiphytic cacti - with the description of two new taxa. Bradleya 18: 2 - 30." type="journal article" year="2000">
Ibisch 
<emphasis box="[1195,1255,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">et al.</emphasis>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
), and the bird genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Vieillot (1816: 31)" authorityName="Vieillot" authorityPageNumber="31" authorityYear="1816" box="[281,625,229,255]" class="Aves" family="Cotingidae" genus="Phibalura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[281,400,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Phibalura</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Vieillot, L. J. P." box="[407,625,229,255]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref34400" refString="Vieillot, L. J. P. (1816) Analyse d'une nouvelle ornithologie elementaire. d'Eterville, Paris." type="book" year="1816">Vieillot (1816: 31)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Snow, D." box="[640,779,229,255]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" refId="ref33987" refString="Snow, D. (1982) The cotingas. Cornell Univ. Press, Ithaca, New York." type="book" year="1982">Snow 1982</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1436,152,564]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,277,267,293]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prado &amp; Lellinger" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="J. W. Sturm" box="[307,607,268,293]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigropaleaceus">
<emphasis box="[307,607,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Sticherus nigropaleaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Jermy &amp; T. G. Walker" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[845,1004,268,293]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="interjectus">
<emphasis box="[845,1004,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. interjectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the only important difference between them is the pattern of cell darkening on the bud scales and on the margins and abaxial surfaces of the branches. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prado &amp; Lellinger" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="J. W. Sturm" box="[300,508,345,370]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigropaleaceus">
<emphasis box="[300,508,345,370]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. nigropaleaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the cell darkening proceeds from the scale apex towards the base, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Jermy &amp; T. G. Walker" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="interjectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. interjectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the process starts from the scale base. Both taxa may have mainly completely dark scales, but close examination will always reveal some scales that are bicolorous and allow deduction of the direction of scale darkening. Also, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prado &amp; Lellinger" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="J. W. Sturm" box="[361,666,461,486]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigropaleaceus">
<emphasis box="[361,666,461,486]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Sticherus nigropaleaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has somewhat less markedly revolute segment margins than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. Gonzales" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Jermy &amp; T. G. Walker" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="interjectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. interjectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Prado, J. &amp; Lellinger, D. B." box="[289,588,500,526]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="98 - 101" refId="ref33175" refString="Prado, J. &amp; Lellinger, D. B. (1996) Observations on the nomenclature and taxonomy of Gleichenia nigropaleacea. American Fern Journal 86: 98 - 101." type="journal article" year="1996">Prado &amp; Lellinger (1996)</bibRefCitation>
further compared 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prado &amp; Lellinger" authorityYear="1996" baseAuthorityName="J. W. Sturm" box="[805,1014,500,525]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nigropaleaceus">
<emphasis box="[805,1014,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. nigropaleaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1980" baseAuthorityName="Christ" box="[1052,1204,500,525]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brevipubis">
<emphasis box="[1052,1204,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. brevipubis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chrysler" authorityYear="1944" baseAuthorityName="Kaulf." box="[1261,1384,500,525]" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Gleicheniaceae" genus="Sticherus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gleicheniales" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="remotus">
<emphasis box="[1261,1384,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">S. remotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in our opinion, these relationships are not very close.
</paragraph>
